  "text": "Mothers play a critical role in childhood acute respiratory infections [CITATION_1] . They are typically the primary caregivers, but older female siblings often take on this role while their mothers are at work. Since older girls may lack the experience of their mothers, the results show that children had an increased risk of coughing, if their mothers were not primary caregivers. This finding was consistent with Rudan et al.'s contention that caregiver experience level is a likely factor in childhood pneumonia [CITATION_2] .",
